<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-177-770  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 177 770.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  March 16 1989 v15 n6 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Different systems for different machines; it's doubtful users willever see one universal operating system.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fabian, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users used to have to create their own operating systems afterpurchasing their hardware.andP;  Then they demanded that vendorsprovide a basic operating system, which they did.andP;  The sameoperating system then became available on different machines fromdifferent vendors, which made things more complex.andO;Plug-compatible vendors developed hardware platforms for the IBMworld that ran all the major operating systems.andP;  Microcomputerswere slightly different.andP;  Vendors other than the manufacturerdeveloped the operating systems, first CP-M, then MS-DOS.andP;  TheMS-DOS operating system is popular because it is so widely used.andO;Almost all applications run under it.andP;  One universal operatingsystem would seem to be desired, but it would have its drawbacks.andO;It would be impossibly large, extremely expensive, and almostuseless to non-computer experts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Operating SystemsMS-DOSStandardizationVendor-Supplied SoftwareUser-Friendliness.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>